WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.441
We have three ways to hold sand together. The obvious question:

2
00:00:03.541 --> 00:00:06.195
if we combine them, do the strengths just add up?

3
00:00:06.866 --> 00:00:10.610
A sticky bio-polymer, cement grown from carbon dioxide, and a

4
00:00:10.710 --> 00:00:13.950
seaweed gel. Each adds its own cohesion to the crust.

5
00:00:14.033 --> 00:00:15.972
Naively you would just stack them. But

6
00:00:16.072 --> 00:00:17.903
three real effects bend that answer.

7
00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:22.274
First, competition. All three fight over the same calcium — and the

8
00:00:22.374 --> 00:00:26.188
cement is the greediest sink, so it starves the polymers a little.

9
00:00:27.966 --> 00:00:31.722
Second, burden. When one cell makes two products at once, they

10
00:00:31.822 --> 00:00:34.893
share one energy budget, so each yields a bit less.

11
00:00:34.966 --> 00:00:39.196
Third, synergy. Some pairs help each other — the polymer's acidic groups

12
00:00:39.296 --> 00:00:42.625
template better crystals — so a bonus term is added back.

13
00:00:42.700 --> 00:00:46.091
Add the cooperation, subtract the competition, and the combined

14
00:00:46.191 --> 00:00:48.973
crust still comes out tougher than any single prong.

15
00:00:49.066 --> 00:00:51.176
And there is a safety bonus: if a storm

16
00:00:51.276 --> 00:00:54.518
defeats one mechanism, the others still hold. Redundancy is

17
00:00:54.618 --> 00:00:57.691
why the team survives conditions that break any soloist.

